animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.OUR REQUIREMENTS FOR PUPPY ADOPTION:
1) PUPPIES WILL ONLY BE PLACED IN HOMES WITH YOUTHFUL, PLAYFUL, DOGS. This helps integrate the dog into your household easier by giving the pup a mentor.
2) In addition to the youthful playful dog, someone MUST also be home at least part of the day. Please do not apply for a puppy if you are gone 8-10 hours a day. It is not a good situation for you or the puppy.
3) You must have plans in place to socialize your puppy properly.
4) Our puppies are not livestock dogs. They must be family pets that are allowed inside the home.

Please watch this short video which demonstrates how puppies learn polite behavior from their adult dog mentors. https://youtu.be/R6N8STRl2aI

Meet Duffy! She is a sweet young thing who loves life! Born about May 2020, Duffy is a well-proportioned pocket Pyr, weighing about 55 pounds. Full of energy and curiosity, she will keep you on your toes as she gets comfortable in your home.

Duffy gets along well with dogs of all sizes, especially if they're playful! Duffy would probably do better in a multiple pet home at this time, because she loves to play. She must have a large, playful doggy companion in her forever home.

She has not been tested with cats.

Duffy can be a tad stubborn when she's afraid, and she's perfected passive resistance! But when she gets over her fear, she's a loving companion with a willingness to please.

Being a little on the smaller side, she'll sometimes need help loading into the car, but she rides well once inside.

Duff-Duff enjoys the merits of a good water puddle, so if fastidiousness is a must for you, she may not be a good match. But if you can overlook a little dirty fun, she'll make a wonderful addition to your family!

SPIN Pyrs are all in foster homes in the Dallas/Fort Worth area. Potential adopters are asked to make travel arrangements if they live elsewhere. All SPIN dogs are spayed or neutered, current on vaccinations and on heartworm prevention. Please go to our website www.SpinRescue.org and fill out an application for this great Great Pyrenees!

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.We are searching for a home for this handsome young man. Moose is going to be an AMAZING dog! When he came in he had no manners and was deathly afraid of other dogs. We do believe he can overcome this with time, but for now, he will be in need of an only dog home. He just needs time and patience. You see, Moose is a 1-year-old chocolate lab pup born to an Amish Breeder. He was given to another young Amish man, because he had something wrong with his eye. The defect made him unsellable, however, it was just cherry eye that could be surgically fixed. He had the surgery and it was a complete success. We can just thank God this kid stepped up. Normally these pups are killed. No $$$...no worth! The fact that we have built a rapport with the Amish community saved this boy's life! One of our previous surrenders gave this young man our information. If you think you can give this boy everything he needs, applications are available on our website www.onedogatatime.us.

animal.description:
Gonza is a true lap dog who loves endless cuddles. She is three years old and an absolute sweetheart who is quiet and calm, with a very wiggly body and waggy tail when excited. She is likely a Beagle/Corgi + a decent mix of breeds and weighs about 30 lbs. Gonza is hesitant around strangers, but warms of quickly. From the first day she arrived she was friendly with our large breed dog, and enjoys his company, although she is not interested in playing with him. Gonza is 100% potty trained and sleeps quietly through the night at the foot of the bed. She also does well on walks and car rides. Gonza is looking forward to a loving home where she can snuggle and be your constant companion.

We would like Gonza's adopter to have a fully fenced in yard - and likely she would do better in a home with kids 10+. 






The adoption fee of $400 will include spay/neuter, microchip, age appropriate/required vaccinations, treatment for heartworm and any other necessary medical treatment to assure a healthy new pup for your family.


IMPORTANT DISCLAIMER: Although we do our best to describe breed, since our pups all come from shelters we can not and will not make any guarantee on breed or size. We can tell you that they are 100% RESCUED! And that is the BEST breed!

If you are interested in adopting/meeting , please visit our website at www.starfishanimalrescue.com or you may complete the online adoption application on our Facebook Page https://www.facebook.com/starfishanimalrescue/app/134425496630143/?ref=page_internal Once you complete and submit your dog adoption application we will set up an appointment to meet this pup!  (the Facebook application will not load from a mobile phone, you must be on a desktop or laptop for this)

*please note that we are a foster home based rescue and we do home visits as part of the adoption process - we are unable to adopt to families who live outside of the Chicago and surrounding suburbs. Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
NO LONGER ACCEPTING APPLICATIONS

Animal Profile: Sonny is an adorable, 3 year old Chihuahua/dachshund mix. He will be joining us from California on January 10th. He was in the shelter with another female Chihuahua that we also will be bringing to Seattle. Sonny, like most little dogs, was pretty overwhelmed at the shelter (can we blame him?). He is very happy to be in safe hands now. Sonny is still a bit overwhelmed, and will need someone to go slow with him at first so he can decompress and settle in. We have no doubt his personality will quickly flourish in foster care! We will post more info as we get to know him.

Seattle Foster Update: Sonny is really settling in well in his foster home! He was shy when he arrived (as expected) but is getting more comfortable each day. He is a total snuggle bug, and often finds his way into his foster's lap whenever he gets a chance. The outside world can still be a bit overwhelming for Sonny, so he has been skittish on walks around loud noises. Sonny would prefer a quieter environment, and an adopter who is committed to working on his training to help build his confidence. Sonny has been all about his humans when he is home, but when he has had a chance to play/interact with other dogs he has done great! He recently had a playdate with a playful puppy and they played great together. Sonny would likely enjoy a canine companion in his forever home. More info to come as he continues to settle in!

Adoption Info: Adoption fee is $500, which includes spay/neuter, current rabies/DAPPV/bordetella vaccinations, microchip, health certificate, and heartworm test. All adoption fees are donations to a Washington non-profit corporation and all donations go to benefit the animals in our rescue.

Apply online at www.DogGoneSeattle.org

Animal History: This dog was rescued from euthanasia at a high-kill shelter in California and will be available for adoption in Seattle, once evaluated in a loving foster home in the greater Seattle area.

animal.description:
ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS
Fenced yard


Hi! My name is Jiggs, but my foster mom calls me Sir Jiggs-A-Lot or Mr Jiggles. I am 14 years old and weigh roughly 14 pounds. I had a family but they unfortunately passed away but thankfully, this nice rescue took me in! They say I’m a shih tzu mix. I look the part but am a little bigger than the average shih tzu so maybe I have something else fun mixed in! I’ve been in my foster home about a month and have finally started coming out of my shell. I’m an old man so I like my sleep, but I still get small, short bursts of energy, which my foster parents really love to watch! I’m fine with other dogs as long as they’re not set on playing with me and could be fine as an only dog as well. I’m a little different because I am deaf but I’m such a good boy! My ideal home would be one with no other dogs or ones that don’t pay me much attention. I’d love to just have a super cozy bed to rest in and be able to come out to explore when I want. As far as potty training goes, I’m really good at giving signals to let you know I need to go. I wear a belly band now just in case and am happy to do so. Mom and Dad don’t crate me now but they think I’d be fine in one although I don’t have a destructive bone in my body. As far as health goes, I am deaf and will need eye drops for the rest of my life, but other than that I feel and have been doing great!! If you’d like to meet me, please message the rescue page! Otherwise, these foster parents of mine may just try to keep me!

If you would like to meet Jiggs send us an email to theloveofk9s@yahoo.com and we will get back to you as quick as we can.

Adoption donation pays for all vetting...my neuter, a heart worm test, all vaccinations, deworming, flea prevention, a microchip and a wellness exam

animal.description:
Meet Molly.  This goofy happy go lucky girl is typical friend lab and at 100 pounds she must be part moose!  Molly is three years old, dog friendly but way too interested in kitties to safely live with them.  She would likely be fine with kids but because of her large size we do not feel comfortable placing her with little ones.

If you are interested in this dog please fill out an online application on our website:                          https://.barkdogfarm.rescuegroups.org/forms/ 

Before applying be sure you have thoroughly researched the breed and will it be compatible with your lifestyle.  
Please be sure all family members are in agreement to adopting and your family is ready to bring dog home now. 
Applicants must be at least 21 years old. 
A volunteer will be in touch to discuss your application and the dog to determine if it is a good match. Your vet and two references will be called.  A virtual home visit done. Once approved a meet and greet at the farm will take place.  If all are in agreement and the animal has received its NH health certificate an adoption contract will be signed and adoption fee paid.  
Adoption fees for dogs are $450. for adults over 12 months, $500 for puppies 12 months and younger.  Fees for seniors, special needs or harder to place dogs will be determined by our Board of Directors.
 All dogs will be altered when adoption is finalized, up to date on age appropriate core vaccines, negative for parasites, heart worm and lyme tested if 6 months or older, microchipped and have a current health certificate.  
Proof of a basic obedience course completed is part of our adoption contract within six months. 
Our descriptions are based on shelter evaluations, input from foster homes and interactions with our volunteers therefore are in no way a guarantee of temperment. 

! Please know we practice Covid-19 guidelines for mask wearing and social distancing.  Only approved applicants are allowed to meet our dogs outdoors at this time. Please email barkingdogfrm@gmail.com with any questions.

Dexter seems to be more nervous around most men including my husband, so I'm assuming whatever happened to him in Texas was caused by a guy. With my husband staying home with the girls and my working, with his fear of doorways and men he would sit outside all day until I got home and we decided that he needs to go somewhere where he's more comfortable and not too scared to come inside when it's so cold. And somewhere without goats because he is not a fan. When he got inside and relaxed, he was fine with my husband, let the girls play with him, and snuggled us including the kid, other dog and cat. We just couldn't figure out how to get him inside when I'm at work and don't want him to freeze.!
If you would like to meet me, please visit our website and complete the pre-adoption application. Once it has been processed then we can make a date to get together!

If you have a dog currently, you should bring him/her along to meet the new dog so we can see how everyone interacts. animal.description:
***Please DO NOT send us inquiries/emails asking if this dog is still available. If a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder- we are still accepting applications for them**

Meister is currently in Houston, TX and can transport to the PNW mid February.

Meister, 2 years old, male, pitbull, 43 lbs. This adorable dog was brought to our attention when he was placed on the euthanasia list in San Antonio, TX. We were able to spring him from the shelter life and are hoping to find his forever home in the PNW. 

Meister has been friendly with every dog he has met. He has been in a foster home with both male and female dogs. If the dog does not want to play with him, he leaves them alone. When Meister saw the dog in his foster home his face lit up and his body didn't stop wiggling. We think he would love a four legged friend to have as a companion. He does not seem overly playful and isn't needing an active playmate. 

He is friendly to both females and males and we've seen no aggression, fear or anxiety. We have no history with kids so we recommend a home with kids 10 years and older. 

Meister is housebroken, but has had some accidents when first in a home. He has done some marking as well, but we know he is a smart boy & will easily catch on once he's taught! He walks great on a leash. 

Meister loves to snuggle, give kisses and lounge around the house. He appears to have low/moderate energy and is not super active. 

Meister would make an amazing emotional support animal as he just loves being with his people! Meister does have separation anxiety and has managed to escape from several crates.  In doing so he has several cuts on his face as we believe we squeezed through  or pushed through the door. He has scratched up a door to get out of the room he was in to find his person. He will need someone who is home more than they are away. He will also need a secure crate/area where he can't get out or destroy anything in trying to get out. 
We would be willing to pay for one training session to help with this behavior with an agreed upon trainer in your area. 

We have no history with cats. 

Meister is an incredibly sweet dog who wants to be loved. We are hopeful someone will be willing to help ease his separation anxiety and will be able to see what an amazing dog he is.

***Listed BREED and AGE - We are taking our best guess on age, breed and size when fully grown. We rarely know a dog's exact age nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time.

The first step in our process is filling out an application. We will review your application as soon as we are able- there are two of us and we do the best that we can. We review applications on a first come first serve basis and look for the best fit/match for dog and applicant.

https://heartoftheunderdog.org/adoption-application

The Animal Rescue Project (www.animalrescueproject.org) is committed to the best possible veterinary care for the pets it rescues and it is looking for adopters who will be similarly committed.

All dogs and puppies are given a general check-up when they enter our program. They receive medication to remove any intestinal parasites (worms), fleas, and ticks they may have. Dogs greater than six months of age are checked for heartworm. If heartworm positive, the Animal Rescue Project treats the disease. Dogs and pups receive all age-appropriate vaccinations for distemper, and dogs greater than four months of age are also vaccinated for rabies, in compliance with State of Michigan laws. All dogs are also microchipped.

Most dogs and older puppies are spayed or neutered before adoption. In the case of puppies not old enough to be safely sterilized, a $50 deposit is required at the time of adoption and is refunded to the adopter with proof of sterilization.

The Animal Rescue Project requires every adopter to establish an active relationship with a veterinarian no later than 10 days after adoption. Adopters will receive a plan for routine veterinary care at the time of adoption and are expected to work with their vet to complete the plan.

You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.
Dog's Name: Odie
Estimated Breed : Pitbull Terrier Mix
Approximate Age: 4 years
Approximate Weight: approx. 60 lbs
Currently Living at: Boarding
Adoption Fee: $375
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
Odie is a very sweet, beautiful brindle boy looking for his forever home and loving family. He loves to give hugs and walks well on a leash. He can be timid about new thing so will need a home with patience. Odie is heartworm positive, but do not worry.... we will pay for his treatment and make him brand new again! Who is ready for kisses and hugs??
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org
Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!
For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.
Please "like" our Facebook Page for the most current events and new dogs.
Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
Tonka has had a bit of rough go of it. She was adopted as a puppy from a shelter in Ohio and living the good life until her human adopted another puppy and because they didn't get along, Tonka was dropped at another shelter. She was adopted again and she and her human moved to Texas where he fell on hard times and had to give her up to another shelter. She sat for 6 weeks unloved and waiting. Tonka lost weight, her tail became bloody from constantly wagging it against the kennel walls in hopes that someone would pet her. Her spirit darkened and she became depressed. That's when DAWG stepped in and got her on the road to health and then sent her to us .
Tonka would really love a forever home that won't leave her again-where she can feel loved, needed and safe. Could that be you?
We do recommend no cats and is iffy about other dogs.

If you would like to meet me, please visit our website and complete the pre-adoption application. Once it has been processed then we can make a date to get together!
All dogs are spayed/neutered, heartworm tested (if over 2 years old), vaccinated, dewormed, flea and tick treated, microchipped and more before adoption. Our adoption policies include: Application, Vet Reference, Landlord approval & Criminal Background Check. We do not do same day adoptions. We request that you call for an appointment after your application has been approved to come and visit the dog of your choice. If you have a dog currently, you should bring him/her along to meet the new dog so we can see how everyone interacts. Please visit our website for additional information. The online application can be found at :https://hsburnettcty.org/adoption-guidelines/

animal.description:
Due to COVID-19 precautions, all animals for adoption through Homeward Trails can be met by appointment only. For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption questionnaire and e-mail it to lindsay.homewardtrails@gmail.com

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE:
http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

Meet Todd and Diana! This sweet bonded pair comes to Homeward Trails from Fayette County, WV. Unfortunately, they were surrendered to the shelter (through no fault of their own!) after some hardships with their first family. Their story is sad, but they are clearly a fun and health duo, used to playtime and very sweet with new people. 

Todd is about 5 years old, 60 lbs and a neutered male, while Diana is 2 years old, 80 lbs and a spayed female. Check out this cute video of them as well. Their foster says they have settled in well, they love to play outside, go running, explore the backyard and snuggle up indoors. They seem sweet and resilient, with some minor signs of previous trauma, but very adaptable and happy dogs!

Adoption Coordinator: Lindsay
Location: Foster Home in DC

The adoption fee for Todd and Diana is $815. This fee INCLUDES spay/neuter and microchip for both dogs.

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

We also provide free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program
